171
00:07:19,930 --> 00:07:22,890
So I want to know, how long am I spending in my introduction?

172
00:07:22,890 --> 00:07:26,450
How long am I spending in part three?

173
00:07:26,450 --> 00:07:27,720
How long is that taking?

174
00:07:27,720 --> 00:07:29,060
So I've got a timer with me.

175
00:07:29,060 --> 00:07:30,050
I'm practicing it.

176
00:07:30,050 --> 00:07:32,810
And I writing down where my time breaks are.

177
00:07:32,810 --> 00:07:34,230
So I run the speech.

178
00:07:34,230 --> 00:07:35,680
I've got a greater sense for it.

179
00:07:35,680 --> 00:07:37,400
Now I sit down reflect again.

180
00:07:37,400 --> 00:07:39,480
And here's where I go in my head.

181
00:07:39,480 --> 00:07:42,730
I'm like, boy, I really like all this material, but I'm tight on time.

182
00:07:42,730 --> 00:07:46,190
And I just have to remind myself, you can't game the system.

183
00:07:46,190 --> 00:07:48,380
It's not just a matter of going faster.

184
00:07:48,380 --> 00:07:49,860
That's not what you want.

185
00:07:49,860 --> 00:07:51,080
I got to cut stuff.

186
00:07:51,080 --> 00:07:53,660
I'm probably in the stage of cutting stuff.

187
00:07:53,660 --> 00:07:57,030
And so at this stage, these cuts hurt.

188
00:07:57,030 --> 00:07:59,600
I really like this section, but it's got to go.

189
00:07:59,600 --> 00:08:02,120
No, maybe I can-- no, seriously, you cannot.

190
00:08:02,120 --> 00:08:04,320
It has to go.

191
00:08:04,320 --> 00:08:05,830
So I'm making those hard cuts.

192
00:08:05,830 --> 00:08:08,100
And that's what's happening in the revisions.

193
00:08:08,100 --> 00:08:09,600
I'm checking those time allocations.

194
00:08:09,600 --> 00:08:12,200

195
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:15,330
Am I spending the most time where I want to be spending the most time or

196
00:08:15,330 --> 00:08:17,010
where I need to be spending the most time?

197
00:08:17,010 --> 00:08:20,230
That timing those chunks is really important information when I'm making

198
00:08:20,230 --> 00:08:24,290
revisions because I'm, like, well, is this matching up with what I want?

199
00:08:24,290 --> 00:08:27,400
And in that sense, I also want to check my overall congruency.

200
00:08:27,400 --> 00:08:32,220
If I said I had three main objectives or three goals for the audience, I

201
00:08:32,220 --> 00:08:35,549
want to look at those goals and say, am I really accomplishing those in

202
00:08:35,549 --> 00:08:36,320
this speech?

203
00:08:36,320 --> 00:08:37,390
If I am, great.

204
00:08:37,390 --> 00:08:40,360
If I'm not, do I need to go back and change those goals?

205
00:08:40,360 --> 00:08:42,340
Do I need to change my sense of what the audience is?

206
00:08:42,340 --> 00:08:46,570
Or do I need to make some revisions to the outline itself?

207
00:08:46,570 --> 00:08:49,110
So I'm doing a pass for congruency.

208
00:08:49,110 --> 00:08:52,730
So then we enter final phase, just style and polish.

209
00:08:52,730 --> 00:08:53,400
So I run it.

210
00:08:53,400 --> 00:08:55,220
Once again, I'll run it twice in a row.

211
00:08:55,220 --> 00:08:58,690
And by now I want to be pretty close to my time mark.

212
00:08:58,690 --> 00:09:01,550
If I've got 10 minutes for the speech, I should be coming in

213
00:09:01,550 --> 00:09:03,350
roughly around there.

214
00:09:03,350 --> 00:09:06,180
I'll probably say this again under delivery.

215
00:09:06,180 --> 00:09:12,620
But if you're presenting a speech for a live audience, you should probably,

216
00:09:12,620 --> 00:09:18,270
in practice, get it to about 85% of your time allocation.

217
00:09:18,270 --> 00:09:24,850
So if you got a 10-minute speech, in practice, ideally you'd want to be

218
00:09:24,850 --> 00:09:26,470
coming in closer to 8:30.

219
00:09:26,470 --> 00:09:30,310
And that's because that means when you get up in front of that audience, you

220
00:09:30,310 --> 00:09:31,840
can play around with them.

221
00:09:31,840 --> 00:09:33,870
If something happens, you can respond to it.

222
00:09:33,870 --> 00:09:34,830
You can talk to them.

223
00:09:34,830 --> 00:09:37,540
You don't have to race, because you're probably going to be going faster in

224
00:09:37,540 --> 00:09:39,280
practice than you will in performance.

225
00:09:39,280 --> 00:09:43,290
So you want to be able to give yourself enough relaxing time to play

226
00:09:43,290 --> 00:09:47,080
around with that audience, have fun, relax a little bit.

227
00:09:47,080 --> 00:09:51,010
And so I want to make sure that I know what my maximum time is so that in

228
00:09:51,010 --> 00:09:54,450
this final stage when I'm timing my chunks, if I've got a 10-minute

229
00:09:54,450 --> 00:09:56,930
speech, I'm coming in between 8 and 1/2 to 9 minutes.

230
00:09:56,930 --> 00:10:01,170
Because then, I don't have to worry about going over when I get into that

231
00:10:01,170 --> 00:10:02,820
actual speech setting.

232
00:10:02,820 --> 00:10:03,960
So I run the speech.

233
00:10:03,960 --> 00:10:04,980
I run it twice again.

234
00:10:04,980 --> 00:10:05,990
I'm timing my chunks.

235
00:10:05,990 --> 00:10:06,890
Reflection.

236
00:10:06,890 --> 00:10:11,330
All right, well, at this point, I should like most of the speech.

237
00:10:11,330 --> 00:10:15,130
And one thing that emerges at this stage is I know where I could

238
00:10:15,130 --> 00:10:16,960
potentially go off on a tangent.

239
00:10:16,960 --> 00:10:18,980
So it's like, oh, I've got a ton of content there.

240
00:10:18,980 --> 00:10:22,630
If I don't watch myself, I'll go off for five minutes talking about that.

241
00:10:22,630 --> 00:10:25,880
So I need to write around that or plan around that.

242
00:10:25,880 --> 00:10:27,550
Or at the very least, I got to know it.

243
00:10:27,550 --> 00:10:29,970
So I'm like, when I reach that point, I'm like, just shut up.

244
00:10:29,970 --> 00:10:30,580
Keep going.

245
00:10:30,580 --> 00:10:31,610
Remember, this works.

246
00:10:31,610 --> 00:10:33,730
Don't go off a tangent.

247
00:10:33,730 --> 00:10:34,770
Don't say that out loud.

248
00:10:34,770 --> 00:10:36,100
Your audience won't know what you're talking about.

249
00:10:36,100 --> 00:10:37,550
